## What happened

.NET 11 removed the built-in DSA implementation on macOS. Apple's native crypto libraries (Security.framework / CryptoKit) never supported DSA, and previously .NET shimmed it through a bundled OpenSSL interop layer on macOS. In .NET 11, that shim was dropped — `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.

DSA has been marked `[Obsolete]` (SYSLIB0047) since earlier releases; .NET 11 completes the removal on platforms without native support.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), your best options:

### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended)

```csharp
// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] message, byte[] signature)
{
    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is pure managed code — works on all platforms with no native dependencies.

### Option 2 — Ship OpenSSL on macOS

Install OpenSSL via Homebrew (`brew install openssl`) and P/Invoke into it directly, but this adds a native dependency and deployment complexity.

---

**TL;DR:** Apple never supported DSA natively; .NET 11 stopped papering over that. Switch signature verification to BouncyCastle for a cross-platform managed solution.
